data.name: label3.Text
data.value:
Long ago, a brilliant scientist named Isaac Newton wondered why apples fall from trees instead of floating away like balloons. One day, as he sat under an apple tree, an apple fell and hit him on the head! That got him thinking.
Newton realized that there was a force that pulls everything towards the ground, like how the apple fell to Earth. He called this force "gravity." Gravity is like a magical invisible glue that keeps us on the ground and makes things fall down instead of up.
It's not just here on Earth—gravity is everywhere in the universe! It's what keeps the Moon circling around the Earth and the Earth circling around the Sun. Without gravity, everything would float away into space!
So, thanks to Isaac Newton and his curious mind, we now understand why things fall down and how gravity keeps our feet firmly planted on the ground.
